response to social inequality, and examines the impact of liberalism on changing attitudes to poverty and charity. Seeing charity as a class duty, elite women structured their benevolent design around the protection, religious salvation, and social regulation of poor children. Janice Harvey explores how these philanthropists overcame the constraints of social conventions for women in polite society, how charity directors devised and implemented institutional aid, and how that aid was used by families and experienced by children. Following the development of the charities through the end of the nineteenth century and into the early twentieth, the book explores the conflict that arose between these institutions and other social services, including those that advocated for foster care and so-called scientific charity. The 1920s marked a major social shift in how child poverty was understood and managed in Protestant Montreal.Despite the gendered obstacles facing women in charity organization, Their Benevolent Design celebrates the remarkable ingenuity and independence of a group of Canadian women in shaping social aid and improving the grim realities of child poverty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPoor children. 0aWomen in charitable workvBiography. 0aWomen in charitable work-Biography. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Provincial, Territorial & Local / Quebec (QC).2bisacsh  aAnglican.  aChristianity.  aMontreal.  aQuebec.  aadoption.  aagency.  aapprenticeship.  acare.  aclass.  acommittee.  aconstrained.  aemotional frontier.  aethic.  aevangelicalism.  afemale.  afoster.  agender.  ahome.  aincorporated societies.  aindustrial school.  ainstitutionalization.  ainterdenominational.  alady.  aliberalism.  amoral reform.  amunicipal assistance.  aneed.  anineteenth centu